1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:09,000
The hard part for many product people is not prompting.
It is getting past installs, Git, folders, builds, and authentication.

2
00:00:09,000 --> 00:00:24,000
PPP starts where familiar browser tools start:
open a project and describe the outcome.

3
00:00:24,000 --> 00:00:39,000
The first result is a real browser game.
Its timer and keyboard behavior are already running, with no refresh.

4
00:00:39,000 --> 00:00:55,000
Now the same conversation crosses the server boundary
and adds product accounts without replacing the game.

5
00:00:55,000 --> 00:01:10,000
Product work is iterative. The first form is not good enough,
so I ask for a better interface and useful errors.

6
00:01:10,000 --> 00:01:34,000
This error comes from the real account boundary. I fix the input,
create a player, sign out, sign back in, and the session survives reload.

7
00:01:34,000 --> 00:01:51,000
Next, Snake becomes a service. The signed-in player saves a score
through a server action into SQLite.

8
00:01:51,000 --> 00:02:06,000
The ranking is server-owned data, not a painted mockup.
The account and score remain after reload.

9
00:02:06,000 --> 00:02:23,000
A product decision changes the shape of the whole service.
Snake is now one game in a platform, without losing its users or data.

10
00:02:23,000 --> 00:02:40,000
One more conversation adds a second game
while preserving everything that already works.

11
00:02:40,000 --> 00:02:54,000
Tetris runs in the browser. Accounts and rankings stay on the server.
Both evolve inside one live product workspace.

12
00:02:54,000 --> 00:02:59,000
Where product conversations become running software.
